The segmentation fault you're encountering could stem from various places in your implementation, but let's focus on the most probable causes, especially given the nature of your operations: Memory management and pointer manipulation within linked list operations.

### Likely Causes of Segmentation Fault

1. **`pop_front` and `pop_back` Methods in an Edge Case:**
   If your list has only one item and you attempt to remove it (either from the front or the back), your code effectively tries to dereference `nullptr`.

   Specifically, in `pop_front`, after deleting the only item, you have:

   ```cpp
   head = head -> next;
   head -> prev = nullptr;
   ```

   And in `pop_back`, after deleting the only item:

   ```cpp
   tail = tail -> prev;
   tail -> next = nullptr;
   ```

   If `head` (or `tail`) becomes `nullptr` after the deletion (which it does when there's only one item in the list), trying to access `head->prev` (or `tail->next`) dereferences `nullptr`, causing a segmentation fault.

### Fixes

1. **`pop_front` Handling for Single Item List:**

   Modify it to check if `head` becomes `nullptr` after advancing it. Do not access `head->prev` if `head` is `nullptr`:

   ```cpp
   void DEList::pop_front() {
       if (!empty()) {
           DEItem* ptr = head;
           head = head->next;
           if (head != nullptr) {  // Check if list is not empty now
               head->prev = nullptr;
           } else {
               tail = nullptr; // Set tail to nullptr if list becomes empty
           }
           delete ptr;
           Itemcount--;
       }
   }
   ```

2. **`pop_back` Handling for Single Item List:**

   Apply a similar check to `pop_back`, ensuring `tail` is not dereferenced if it becomes `nullptr`:

   ```cpp
   void DEList::pop_back() {
       if (!empty()) {
           DEItem* ptr = tail;
           tail = tail->prev;
           if (tail != nullptr) {  // Check if list is not empty now
               tail->next = nullptr;
           } else {
               head = nullptr;  // Set head to nullptr if list becomes empty
           }
           delete ptr;
           Itemcount--;
       }
   }
   ```

3. **`push_front` and `push_back` Improvements:**

   When adding the first item to the list (`empty() == true` branch), you need to ensure `ptr->next` and `ptr->prev` are set to `nullptr` to explicitly define the list boundaries for a single item:

   ```cpp
   void DEList::push_front(int new_val) {
       DEItem* ptr = new DEItem();
       ptr->val = new_val;
       ptr->next = nullptr; // Ensure next is nullptr
       ptr->prev = nullptr; // Ensure prev is nullptr
       if (empty()) {
           head = ptr;
           tail = ptr;
       } else {
           ptr->next = head;
           head->prev = ptr;
           head = ptr;
       }
       Itemcount++;
   }
   ```

   And similarly for `push_back`.

By carefully managing how you manipulate pointers, especially in cases where your list transitions between states (empty, single-item, multiple-items), you can avoid accessing illegal memory and hence mitigate segmentation faults.

